tables.Fastpitch softball: 12 in mm in circumference ( 11 in mm for children 10 and under), less dense than a baseball , optic yellow

tables.Baseball: No longer than 42 in mm . Must be made of wood at the professional level; may be made of aluminum in high school and college.

tables.Baseball: 90 ft m
tables.Fastpitch softball: 60 ft m

tables.Baseball: No, except in youth leagues such as Little League
tables.Fastpitch softball: Used in games under WBSC rules; not used in NCAA

tables.Baseball: Variable distance from home plate is mandatory in professional and university leagues and optional in youth leagues. Many youth leagues, such as Little League , use a constant distance from home plate.
tables.Fastpitch softball: Variable distance from home plate, depending on the individual field. (maximum of 250 ft m )
tables.Slowpitch softball: Constant distance from home plate, although some less organized leagues have no fences.

tables.Baseball: 60 ft 6 in m
tables.Fastpitch softball: Varies by level: 40 ft m (youth), 43 ft m (adult women) or 46 ft m (adult men)
tables.Slowpitch softball: Varies by level: 46 ft m (youth), 50 ft m (adult)

tables.Baseball: Raised sloping mound, radius of 9 ft m , maximum height 10 in cm
tables.Fastpitch softball: Flat circle, the radius of 8 ft m , marked with a white chalk circle

tables.Baseball: Nine
tables.Fastpitch softball: Nine

tables.Baseball: A designated hitter (DH) may bat in place of a pitcher (rule varies by league; some levels allow DHs for other fielders)
tables.Fastpitch softball: One designated player (DP) may bat in place of a fielder.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Some leagues allow an arbitrary number of extra players , up to the entire roster.

tables.Baseball: No player substituted for may return to the game, including the replaced player if the DH takes a defensive position. Under high school rules in the United States, a player may be substituted for and return to the game once. A pitcher who leaves the game may return, but only as a fielder (not the pitcher or DH).
tables.Fastpitch softball: Free defensive substitutions, provided each player occupies the same position in the batting order. If the DP takes a defensive position, the replaced player cannot return to the game.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Free defensive substitutions, provided each player occupies the same position in the batting order.

tables.Baseball: Allowed.
tables.Fastpitch softball: Allowed.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Not allowed; the batter is out if contact is made.

tables.Baseball: Batter is not out unless bunting.
tables.Fastpitch softball: Batter is not out unless bunting.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Batter is generally out. In many recreational leagues, a batter is allowed one foul ball with two strikes, with the second being an automatic out.

tables.Baseball: Awarded first base unless swing, pitch in the strike zone, or no attempt made to avoid being hit.
tables.Fastpitch softball: Awarded first base unless swing, pitch in the strike zone, or attempt made to intentionally be hit, although this is rarely called by the umpire.

tables.Baseball: Allowed at any time the ball is live (i.e. when "time" is not called).
tables.Fastpitch softball: Allowed once the ball leaves the pitcher's hand; runners may not leave base if the pitcher has the ball within the circle.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Generally not allowed, although some levels may permit stealing after a pitched ball crosses the plate or touches the ground.

tables.Baseball: Same rules as for base stealing
tables.Fastpitch softball: Same rules as for base stealing
tables.Slowpitch softball: Runner is usually permitted to take a lead after the ball leaves the pitcher's hand, but must return to base between pitches if the ball is not put into play. The runner can be called out for taking a lead before the pitch.

tables.Baseball: Any method; in practice, usually overhand.
tables.Fastpitch softball: Underhand; no speed or arc restrictions.
tables.Slowpitch softball: Underhand; must travel in an arc and within certain height restrictions (a common range is between 6 and 12 ft m above the ground). Umpire can call a pitch "illegal" while in flight.

tables.Baseball: Most infractions punished as a balk .
tables.Fastpitch softball: The ball remains live. If the batter reaches base successfully and all runners advance, no penalty; otherwise, the play is negated, the pitch attempt is automatically a ball and runners advance one base.
tables.Slowpitch softball: The ball remains live. If the batter does not swing, the pitch is automatically a ball.
